Idea Gold Scheduler – Exact-Fairness Optimiser
(specification rev 2025-05-xx – replaces previous heuristic / Hare-Niemeyer design)

1 Project Goal
Create a Streamlit tool that produces a provably most-balanced on-call schedule for one 4-week block.
Balance is measured in points (each shift template carries a points value).

Fairness target	Requirement
Per-label points	Every resident’s points on each label should equal their fractional share as closely as mathematically possible.
Weekend points	Within each role, deviations from individual weekend targets are kept as close together as possible; the residual spread should not exceed one indivisible weekend-shift step whenever feasible. Equal total points must not conceal avoidable weekend concentration.
Total points	Across all labels, the difference between any two full-participation residents is minimised; ideal bound is ± 1 point.
If perfect equality is impossible	The optimiser returns the schedule with minimum possible deviation and reports residual gaps.

2 Hard Constraints
Shift templates
label, role (Junior / Senior), night_float flag, thu_is_weekend flag, points.

Participants
Lists of juniors and seniors; per-resident flag for night-float eligibility.

Absences

Leave – compensated (quota unchanged).

Rotator – uncompensated (quotas scaled by active_days / block_span).

Night-float overlay
Per-shift coverage patterns and explicit coverer date windows; only eligible
residents of the matching role may cover them. Covered cells leave regular demand,
carry no regular points, and the coverer's window plus configured rest days blocks
regular assignments as an uncompensated absence.

Rest spacing
A resident's regular shifts must respect min_gap. Night-float coverage uses the
overlay assignment's own post-block rest days rather than the regular gap rule.

Role match
Juniors cannot fill senior shifts and vice-versa.

One assignment per slot
Each (day, label) must be covered by exactly one resident.

3 Optimisation Model (Mixed-Integer Programming)
Symbol	Definition
R	residents
D	days in block
L	shift labels
x[r,d,l] ∈ {0,1}	1 ⇔ resident r works label l on day d
P[l]	points value of label l
W[d,l]	1 ⇔ (d,l) is a weekend slot

Derived sums
Copy
Edit
label_pts[r,l]   = Σ_d P[l]·x[r,d,l]
total_pts[r]     = Σ_l label_pts[r,l]
weekend_pts[r]   = Σ_{d,l|W[d,l]=1} P[l]·x[r,d,l]
Target values
Fractional targets t_label[r,l], t_total[r], t_weekend[r] come from proportional shares (including availability and carryover policy) but are not forced; deviations are penalised.

Additional variables
less
Copy
Edit
dev_label[r,l]  ≥ |label_pts[r,l]  − t_label[r,l] |
dev_total[r]    ≥ |total_pts[r]    − t_total[r]   |
dev_weekend[r]  ≥ |weekend_pts[r]  − t_weekend[r]|
max_dev         ≥ dev_total[r]     ∀ r
weekend_residual[r] = weekend_pts[r] − t_weekend[r]
Objective (lexicographic)
Minimise uncovered regular-demand slots first; coverage dominates every fairness
tier, so a fillable slot is never sacrificed for a tidier point spread.

Then minimise max_dev (tightest overall-points spread).

Then minimise Σ dev_total.

Then minimise each role's maximum signed weekend-residual spread. This soft,
target-relative guardrail prevents an equally good total-points schedule from
hiding an avoidable 4-vs-0 weekend concentration while still respecting leave,
caps, reductions, penalties, and carryover-adjusted targets.

Then minimise Σ dev_weekend.

Then minimise Σ dev_label.

(Implementation uses a dominance-weighted sum in this order: coverage ≫ maximum
total deviation ≫ summed total deviation ≫ weekend residual-spread guardrail ≫
summed weekend deviation ≫ per-label deviation ≫ preferences.)

Solver
Use OR-Tools CP-SAT (open-source, handles ≥ 10k binaries easily).
Typical solve time ≤ 60 s for 40 residents × 28 days × 10 labels on Streamlit Cloud.

